Man, lemme tell ya, helpin' folks, that's what gets me goin'. I wanna be workin' with kids who've had a rough go, ya know, abused and neglected.  And I wanna help families that are fallin' apart. I'm talkin' 'bout real help, the kinda that makes a difference.

I believe in treatin' folks right, doin' the right thing, and always tryin' to be better.  It ain't just about social work, it's about livin' right.  See, I always wanted to help folks, but I didn't know how.  Back in school, I saw a lot of folks runnin' from their problems, doin' things that weren't right.  That's why I got my Psychology degree, figured it would help me understand.

One time, I met this young kid, just sixteen,  scared outta his wits.  His folks were treatin' him awful.  I knew I had to do somethin'. I talked to the cops, told 'em what I knew.  Turns out, the law couldn't do much, so they asked me to talk to the parents.  When I did, they were nervous, tryin' to make excuses for how they treated their own son.

That's when I knew, I gotta be a social worker. Gotta help these kids, protect 'em from folks who don't know how to treat 'em right.

And let me tell ya, fairness matters. We say everyone's important, but we act like we all gotta be the same.  I ain't buyin' it. I'm gonna stand up for what's right, fight for the folks who can't fight for themselves.  I've always done that, standin' up against bullies, racists, anyone tryin' to push folks down.  That's my way, and it ain't gonna change.

Well now, lemme tell ya 'bout this here sleep stuff.  Seems like there's two ways folks look at it: the insides of your head, and what's goin' on around ya. 

First, ya got the folks who say it's all in your genes, like inheritin' a bad back or a love for chili. They talk 'bout stuff like your brain cells and how they work, like that there orexin thingy.  They did some tests on mice, sayin' that these orexin fellas tell ya when to sleep and when to stay awake.  They found that messin' with these little fellas can make a mouse sleepy or wired.  So, if you got a messed up orexin, maybe that's why you can't sleep right.

Then ya got the folks who say it's all 'bout your life, like your job, your fam, and who you hang with. They say things like where ya live, your money situation, and even what color ya are can mess with your sleep.  

So, this paper here is talkin' about both sides of this sleep story. They're lookin' at all the studies and tryin' to figure out which one makes more sense. They even talkin' 'bout different kinds of sleep problems, like when you just can't fall asleep or when you fall asleep but can't stay asleep.

Alright, so this here paper's talkin' 'bout somethin' called Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD for short.  It's kinda like this, see?  Some folks, they hear just fine, but their brains, well, their brains ain't quite cuttin' it when it comes to understandin' what they hear.  Like, they can hear you talkin', but they might have trouble makin' sense of it all, or maybe they can't tell where the sounds are comin' from.  We're gonna break it down into three parts: what CAPD is, how ya tell if someone's got it, and what a teacher can do to help out a kid in the classroom that's dealin' with this.   

First off, CAPD is like a glitch in the brain's sound center. It ain't that their ears ain't workin', it's that their brain's havin' trouble processin' all the sounds it's gettin'.  They might hear a word, but they can't quite figure out what it means, or they might hear lots of different sounds at once and not be able to tell 'em apart.   People first started talkin' 'bout this kinda thing back in the 50s, but it took a while to figure out what was goin' on.   

Now, there ain't no one test that can tell ya for sure if someone's got CAPD, but there are ways to figure it out.  Doctors and teachers might use tests and watch how a kid listens and responds to sounds, seein' if they're havin' any trouble. It's kinda like when you're watchin' a kid play, you can tell if they're strugglin' with somethin' just by watchin' 'em.

So, what can a teacher do if they've got a kid in their class with CAPD? Well, that's what we're gonna talk about next.

So, this play, Twelfth Night, it's sayin' somethin' about how usin' disguises, even if it works for a while, can mess ya up real bad. If you keep pretendin' to be someone you ain't, you might just lose yourself completely. The problem is, if you stop the charade, you might hurt people's feelings. See, some folks might not care if you tricked 'em, but others, they'll be real mad and think you're a phony.

Now, when it comes to pretendin' to be the opposite gender, that's a whole other can of worms. It makes you wonder, why'd they even do it in the first place? Like, why ditch their own skin and try to be someone else? In Viola's case, it's about stayin' safe. She's in a new place, and she figures if she pretends to be a guy, folks won't mess with her so much. 

It works, but now she's all alone, cut off from the other women. And to make things worse, she's so good at playin' the guy role that Olivia, this rich lady, falls for her! Olivia even calls her "husband", can you believe that? And then there's Orsino, the Duke, who's got feelings for Viola, even though she's playin' a dude. It's a whole tangled mess.

But maybe that's the point. Maybe this play is sayin' that pretendin' can help folks figure out what they really feel.  Olivia and Orsino, maybe they were hidin' some feelings they didn't even know they had. Maybe Olivia's not even really into Cesario, but she's just so used to lookin' at folks and judgin' 'em by their looks, that she falls for the act. Once she sees Sebastian, who's Viola's twin brother, she forgets all about Cesario.

Well, lemme tell ya, them Germans, they weren't exactly known for bein' nice to folks when they were runnin' things. Especially in that place they called South West Africa, now Namibia. They done messed up real bad, killed a whole bunch of Ovaherero and Nama folks. Now, I ain't sayin' all the Germans were bad, mind ya. They ran things different in different places, just like folks do today. 

When them Brits took over in East Africa after the war, they found a whole lot of Africans could read and write, thanks to the Germans. Seems like they did alright in some places, like Kamerun. But down in South West Africa, it was a whole different story.

They basically left it up to those missionary folks to teach the natives, and the government didn't give 'em much help. But for the white folks, they built schools and made sure them missionaries were doin' things right.  Makes ya wonder what kinda thinking was goin' on there, huh?

Anyway, long story short, most of the folks in South West Africa couldn't read or write after the Germans left. It was like they never even tried. Now, I'm not sayin' it was all the Germans' fault, but those policies they had sure didn't help.

There's a whole lotta books written about how the Germans ran things in their colonies, mostly by them Germans themselves back in the day. Then some folks from England started doin' some studies, comparin' how things were done in different places.

One fella, Cohen, he wrote a book about how things were different in South West Africa and East Africa. He said it all comes down to the fact that South West Africa had a lot more white folks livin' there. 

Now, South West Africa wasn't exactly a hotbed of activity, but it wasn't too bad either. There were a whole lot more white folks there than in any of the other German colonies.

Listen up, folks! Music's changed a whole lot in the last hundred years. There's so many dang styles now, it's hard to keep track! You got your rock, your country, your jazz, your rap, and a whole mess of others. And get this, each one of those has a bunch of little sub-genres, like little branches on a tree.

Now, Heavy Metal rock? That's a real wild one. It's been around for about 40 years and it's got all kinds of flavors. It's like a big ol' potluck, everyone bringin' their own dish. Some folks like it dark and moody, others like it loud and fast. You got your death metal, your thrash metal, your power metal, and more than I can even remember. 

It's gotten so crazy that it's hard to say exactly what makes something "heavy metal" anymore. It's like a chameleon, changin' colors all the time to fit in with whatever's popular. But even though it's all mixed up now, it all started somewhere.

You see, Heavy Metal is more than just music. It's a whole movement, like a big ol' family. It's about bein' loud, bein' proud, and bein' different. It's about takin' what you got and makin' it your own.

It's got this dark side to it, kinda like a storm cloud.  It's got more bass, more guitars, more drums, more everything! The guys in these bands are real musicians, they know their stuff. And let's be honest, a little bit of drugs never hurt nobody, right? 

It's like the Beatles, even they got in on the action with songs like "Helter Skelter."  Talk about dark!

Well, lemme tell ya, this fella Rousseau, he was a dreamer, sorta like those fancy Surrealists, but he was doin' it way back before they came along.  See, he painted this picture, "The Dream," back in 1910, and it ain't just some gal starin' at pretty things in her sleep. It's like he's puttin' his own hopes and dreams on that canvas, ya know?

This guy, he wanted folks to think he was a real artist, to be respected by the fancy art crowd. But here's the catch: he was stuck between a rock and a hard place. He wanted to be accepted, but he also wanted to paint his own dang way.  

Now, this Rousseau fella, he wasn't born with a silver spoon in his mouth. He worked for the government, collectin' tolls, and never had any fancy art lessons. He lost his wife and kids, too, which left him pretty heartbroken. So, he took up paintin' as a way to make somethin' of himself and find some peace. He wasn't tryin' to be all fancy and highbrow like some of the other artists, he just wanted to paint what he saw and felt.

But the art world, well, it can be a tough nut to crack.  He was startin' late compared to all the other artists makin' a name for themselves. He wanted to be part of that crowd, to be accepted, but he had to choose: follow the rules or stay true to himself. "The Dream," that's where it all comes together, ya know? It's like a snapshot of his struggle, his desire to be recognized and his fear of losin' his own voice.

A whole bunch of smart folks have said that ethics and beauty are like two sides of the same coin. I reckon they're right. Like that poet Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know."  We learn most things in life by reading books or doin' things, but we just kinda *know* when somethin's right or wrong, or when somethin's beautiful, without havin' to think too hard about it.  

Ethics and beauty ain't about tellin' ya what to do or what to think. It's more about tryin' to figure out *why* somethin' is beautiful or why somethin' is right. Like, when we talk about a painting bein' good, we might talk about the colors and the shapes, but that don't really explain why it makes us feel somethin'. It's like when you're asked about your favorite song, you just gotta say, "There's just somethin' about it," ya know?

Same goes for morals. We can talk about right and wrong all day long, but it's hard to put it into words. It's like Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." There's always somethin' more to it than just the words.  

I think that's what makes art and morals so powerful. They touch somethin' deep inside us that we can't always explain.  It's like when you read a good book, or see somethin' truly beautiful. It just makes ya feel somethin'. And I think that's why they're so connected.

Germany today is a powerful country, united and full of its own unique culture. You can feel this culture everywhere, from Munich in the shadow of the Alps all the way to Kiel by the Baltic Sea. It's the same story from Cologne on the Rhine River, through the heart of Germany, and to Dresden, that cool Saxon city on the Elbe.  It makes sense that Germany, as we know it now, came from all sorts of different places and people.

The land we know as Germany has been home to Germans for ages. Where the name "Germany" came from is something folks still argue about. Some say it comes from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, back when they lived across the Rhine River and fought those Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar, way back when, first used the word "Germanus" in his writings about the Gallic Wars. He used it to tell the difference between the Gauls he conquered and those pesky Germanic tribes who kept crossing the Rhine (Caesar, 50-40 BC). Some think he got the word from the Gauls themselves.  Others think it comes from the spear they used in battles, called a "ger" (O.E.D, 2010), or maybe from an old Irish word meaning "to shout," because, well, Germans were known for being loud (Names of Germany).

Tacitus, a Roman historian, wrote way back in 98 AD about the origins of the Germans. He said they were the original people in Germany, not mixed with anyone else (Tacitus, 98).  He thought it would be crazy for anyone to leave Asia, Africa, or even Italy to come to Germany! Who would want to live in a wild, cold place with grumpy people? (Tacitus, 98).

And who would leave Rome for Germany? Not the Romans, not at first anyway. They might send out armies to grab stuff from Germany or fight battles, but they mostly just went back home to their big empire.  As the Germanic tribes popped up around the first century, they lived right on the edge of the Roman Empire. They traded goods they took from the land and even fought for the Romans in their army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

Man, I was lookin' at this thing, just starin' at it.  My mind was workin' but not really gettin' anywhere. I was takin' it all in, you know, like a scientist or somethin', but it wasn't clickin' for me.  Thoughts were poppin' up and disappearin' faster than a fly at a picnic. It was like my brain was on autopilot, just processin' the sights without really thinkin' about 'em. 

This one time, this art fella I knew told me about this book, "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain."  I always wanted to learn how to draw, ever since I was a kid, and this book promised to teach ya everything, even how your brain makes sense of lines.  One trick it had was to put a square around whatever you're lookin' at, like a frame.  So, instead of lookin' at this whole mess, you're just focusin' on that one part, like a bowl of fruit on a table.  

But lookin' at this thing, I couldn't picture that frame. I was just overwhelmed, man.  Like, Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved green, and all those fancy Italian guys painted with every color under the sun. I was tryin' to think, "Maybe this is my thing, my art, my story." But all I could think was, "Work in Brown."

So there I was, holdin' this thing, my hand ready to go.  My muscles were tensed up, like I was about to do somethin' important. And then I did it.  Water swirlin', clean and clear, stuff fallin' away.  My hand went for the toilet handle again, this time with more force. I swear, that brown thing was stuck like glue.  

Mop in one hand, lookin' like a fool in my green tie, I stared at this mess someone left behind.  A few more flushes, a few more moments of quiet contemplation, and then I reached for the toilet paper.  I wrapped it around my hand like I was mummifyin' somethin'.  

I stood up straight, then bent over, my hand reaching into the bowl, like I was checkin' on a turkey in the oven...

Listen, folks, these young whippersnappers are dyin' behind the wheel! It ain't just some fluke, there's a whole bunch of stuff goin' on, ya know?  The big brains at the National Institutes of Health say those teen brains ain't even ready for the danger of drivin', just plain greenhorns, that's all.  And that lack of experience, well, it's a recipe for disaster. More crashes, more rollovers, even more speedin' and drivin' off the road, ya hear?

Now, ain't nothin' worse than those teenagers cruisin' around with their buddies, and we all know they do it all the time.  Some fancy-pants group in California did a study, showed it plain as day – the more buddies in the car, the more trouble they get into.

So California and some other states, they're tryin' to help out, givin' these young'uns temporary licenses, limitin' their hours and who they can have in the car.  But that's like puttin' a bandage on a bullet wound, ya know?

The real problem is, these kids just ain't ready to handle the car, plain and simple. Some smart fella, Marvin Zuckerman, he says 18 ain't even old enough! He's done some studies, shows that young folks just love to take risks, get that thrill, ya get me?  So maybe we should wait a bit longer, let 'em grow up some, before they're behind the wheel.

We keep lettin' 'em drive, it's gonna be a bloodbath out there! All those baby boomers' kids, they'll be drivin' soon, and it'll be chaos!  We need new laws, somethin' to keep these kids safe. Schools can teach 'em about drivin', but no one under 18 gets behind the wheel, plain and simple.  Then maybe a temporary permit, and some practice with a grown-up.

Look, it ain't rocket science, folks! We gotta do somethin' before more kids end up in the graveyard. National laws, that's what it takes.  We can save lives, I tell ya!

So I was lookin' through these old Edison movies, see, the ones from way back when, and I found a bunch of these trick films.  There were fifteen of 'em, made between 1895 and 1901.  These movies, they ain't your regular stuff, they use some fancy editing tricks to make ya think things are happenin' that ain't.

I spent a good amount of time lookin' at these flicks, tryin' to figure out how they worked their magic.  Most of 'em, they stick to the same old ways, ya know? They're shot in one spot, like they're on a stage, and the camera just sits there, no movin' around.  They use long shots and medium shots, never gettin' close up on nothin'.  And each movie, well, it's like one big idea, one shot, boom, it's over.

But then there's a few of these later ones, they start doin' somethin' different, like usin' more than one shot in a movie. It's like they're tryin' something new.

One thing that's real common in these trick films is that they're all shot inside, like they're on a stage.  The camera just sits there, watchin' the action go on, never movin'. Kinda like how they used to do it in vaudeville shows.  So the folks in the movies, they just walk back and forth, never comin' closer or goin' further away from the camera.

And because they're all shot in one spot, they use long shots and sometimes medium shots, but never nothin' close up. That's 'cause they wanted folks to see the whole thing, just like at a play.

And these movies, they're real short, just a minute or less, 'cause each one is like one big idea. They're mostly just a bunch of little tricks, like makin' somethin' disappear or reappear, kinda like magic.

Now, here's the thing, sometimes what looks like one shot in the movie, it might actually be a bunch of shots put together to make the trick work.  Take this one movie, "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots," for instance. It looks like it's all one shot, but if you look real close, you can see where they cut between shots to make it look like her head's been cut off.

This John Taylor fella, he was all about bein' a good ol' Republican, ya know?  He was a farmer, through and through, but even him talkin' politics, he was a straight shooter, always speakin' his mind about freedom and how the government should run. See, he thought farm life was the best, and that's what shaped his whole view on everything. He wanted to keep things simple, protect the farmers, and that's what drove his ideas about the government, the Constitution, even the courts.

John believed America had a real shot at buildin' somethin' special, somethin' better than what Europe had.  Since we didn't have all that old-world baggage, we could start fresh, build a system where folks could govern themselves. He was all about folks havin' rights, natural rights, that's what he called 'em, and he said if one right gets messed with, they all start fallin' apart. Government shouldn't be messin' with those rights none. He said back in the "wild west," the strong guys always took what they wanted, but in a civilized society, that ain't right.

To make this perfect society, John thought we needed a government that understood both the good and bad in people. He was a firm believer in good and evil, that folks are born with 'em both. He said, "Government's run by people, so it's gonna have all the good and bad that people have."  He thought good government protected your stuff, helped farmers, and kept people from gettin' too greedy.  He believed even if a government was run by scoundrels, it'd still work if it was built on those good principles.

He thought folks are naturally selfish, but that's not always bad. It's only bad when folks get greedy and try to take advantage of others.  A good government keeps folks in line, but we gotta watch it close so it don't start doin' bad things itself.

John, like a lot of his Republican friends, wanted a government that stuck to the Constitution. He wanted it small and simple, just doin' what the Constitution said, nothin' more. He knew a big government cost a lot of money and could easily turn into a tyrant. But he said just readin' the words ain't enough, gotta understand what the fellas who wrote it meant. He thought the Declaration of Independence was more important, 'cause it said America was a bunch of states, each lookin' out for themselves, not one big country.

Alright, so listen up, we had this project, see, and it was about gettin' folks to ditch their cars and  walk or bike to work.  Figure 17, that there chart, shows things went south around the third month. Kinda bummed us out, to be honest.  

Now, it's New England, so winter hit hard, right?  Folks ain't walkin' or bikin' much when it's snowin' or freezin'. December, that's when the semester ends, everyone's swamped with schoolwork and whatnot.  Fillin' out a log for the project?  Yeah, that probably slipped their minds.  Then December's when the holidays hit, and everyone's scatterin' for the hills.  Students and teachers gone, ain't nobody on campus for a whole month.  Come January, things start up again, but by then, the log entries are still low.  

Now, I reckon any project starts with a bang, folks all excited, then it fades a little.   To try and keep things goin', we had this "Carpool Challenge Week" in March, like a big ol' push to get folks back on track.  Worked, too, entries went up.  But heck, keepin' things movin' when folks are busy or on break? That's a challenge right there.

Another thing is, folks love their cars.  It's part of our culture.  Gotta give 'em somethin' to make 'em wanna ditch the wheels.  We gave out gift cards, you know, to restaurants, coffee shops, even massage places.  But I wonder if somethin' bigger woulda worked, like a shiny new bike, a hybrid car, or maybe even a fancy electric one.  

The prizes stayed the same the whole time.  Maybe if we'd upped the ante, like sayin', "Hey, in December, we're givin' away bikes!" and then, in January, "And in January, it's a hybrid car!"  Maybe that'd have kept folks interested.

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout these fancy things called ETFs, they're like index funds but fancier, kinda like a stock but traded on the market. You know how index funds track somethin' like the whole market, but ETFs are more like pickin' a few stocks to follow.  And here's the deal, they're cheaper than those mutual funds, but ya gotta pay a little somethin' somethin' each time ya buy or sell 'em, just like regular stocks.  The good thing about ETFs is there's a whole bunch of 'em out there, so ya can find one for just about anything.  Now, some folks say ETFs give ya all the good stuff of a fund, like spreadin' your money around, but ya gotta look close and make sure they ain't just talkin' a big game.  

Now lemme tell ya 'bout this one ETF, IHF, I'm gonna compare it to the top ten stocks it's made up of. I'm gonna see if just buyin' those ten stocks straight up is better than buyin' the whole ETF.  

See, these ten stocks make up most of what's in the ETF, like 63% or somethin'.  So we're gonna see if they act like the whole ETF, like if they make the same kinda money or have the same kinda risk.  I'm gonna figure out somethin' called "Beta," which tells ya how risky somethin' is, and "return," which is how much money ya make.

Well, turns out, the ten stocks made a little more money than the whole ETF, like 6% more. And they were a little less risky too.  So it looks like buyin' those ten stocks straight up might be a better deal. But I gotta make sure it ain't just luck, ya know?

So I'm gonna check somethin' called "standard deviation," which tells ya how much the price of somethin' goes up and down. If the ten stocks are less risky than the ETF, then maybe buyin' just those ten stocks is the way to go.

Alright, so Poe, he thought "Dream-Land" was one of his best poems, ya know? Now, in this poem, he uses this word "Thulé", like a fancy name for a place.  Turns out, some smart guy named Mabbott figured out that Poe got this word from an old fella named Virgil. Virgil wrote about this island called Thulé way up north, past Britain, where folks back then thought the world ended.  Now, Virgil definitely used the word, but there's this other guy, Goethe, who Poe really liked.  Poe was a big fan of German writers. 

This whole thing about Thulé is important 'cause it shows Poe knew his stuff, ya know? This guy, Arndt, wrote a book comparing Poe's poem to Goethe's, and he thinks Poe was basically copying him.  

Goethe was a big deal back then. This book of his called "Faust" was super famous, with two parts, one in 1808 and the other when he died, 1832.  There's this little poem in the second part of "Faust" called "The King of Thulé." It's about this king who loses his wife, and after she dies, he just drinks and cries all the time.  He's so sad he decides to die too, and he gives away everything except this fancy goblet his wife gave him. He goes to a cliff, throws the goblet in the ocean, closes his eyes, and that's it.

Now, the King of Thulé, he's kinda like Poe's character in "Dream-Land," maybe a dark reflection of Poe's own sadness and drinking problems.  "Faust" was even made into a play in 1842, just before Poe used the word "Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."  

Poe only uses "Thulé" a couple of times in his writing. Once in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land" at the beginning and end of the poem.  You could almost read them together, like they're friends. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about this dark, lonely place called Thulé, haunted by dead friends, and everything's just gray and sad.  It's like he's stepped right into the King of Thulé's story.

Goethe was a big shot, and Poe would've known him, even if it was just 'cause Poe liked Tennyson. Plus, everyone was copying Goethe back then.

So, some lady named Jennifer Palmer went and slipped on some applesauce in a grocery store, hurt her back real bad.  Now she's trying to sue the store, sayin' the manager knew about the spill and didn't clean it up for half an hour 'cause he was busy eatin' dinner. She wants the store to pay her extra money, kinda like a punishment, 'cause she says the manager was bein' a real jerk. 

See, in California, ya gotta prove the store manager did somethin' real bad on purpose, like he meant to hurt her or was just plain nasty.  The lady's sayin' he knew folks were slipin' and fallin' on spills all the time, but still didn't care. That's a pretty good argument, maybe even mean enough to get her extra money.

It all happened back in 2009.  Two employees told the manager, Paul, about the spilled applesauce. He just told 'em to go away 'cause he was eatin'.  Then, half an hour later, Jennifer goes and slips, hurts herself somethin' fierce.

The lady's lawyer is sayin' this ain't just a simple accident, it's like the manager was willfully ignorin' the danger, like he didn't care if someone got hurt. That's what they mean by "despicable" I guess.

So now the judge's gotta decide if the manager was really that bad, bad enough to pay extra money.  That's a tough one, huh?

Y'all know, back when I took that Islam class at CBC, like four years ago, we talked a lot about whether Islam was a mean religion or not. Seems even more important now, don't ya think? After 9/11, the media went from really hating on Muslims and folks like that to bein' all soft on 'em. Like, could you imagine back in 2001 havin' a president named Barack Obama, with his Muslim family history? No way!

Now, this book about Muhammad, it's got me confused. See, I always thought he was a real tough guy, conquerin' tribes and makin' 'em turn Muslim. But this book paints him as a martyr, misunderstood and humble. People just came to him, seein' the truth in his words.  It's like they're tryin' to make him out to be some kinda saint.

And get this - there are some things about Muhammad's story that sound a lot like stuff Jesus did. Like, he turned milk and meat into enough for forty guys! It makes me wonder if they're tryin' to steal Jesus' thunder, y'know? They're downplayin' Jesus' miracles to make Muhammad look bigger.

The book also tells a lot of stories about folks convertin' to Islam on their own, but it's all hearsay. They say "So-and-so told me, who heard it from so-and-so." Makes it sound fishy to me.

What really bothers me is how they try to make Muhammad seem so perfect, humble, and wise. But history ain't got nothin' on that, no sir. I just can't believe Muslims today know the whole story about how Muhammad got so powerful.

Well, lemme tell ya, it seems like them fancy theologians done went and changed up Jesus's teachings somethin' fierce since he kicked the bucket. Kinda like how my buddy took my pool plans and made 'em his own, but didn't ask first.

Look, the world's gettin' more open-minded every day, like a rusty gate finally swingin' open. Now, some folks are stuck in their ways, like a mule in a ditch, but they ain't gonna change the whole darn world. More and more folks are gonna start lookin' back and seein' what got added to Christianity over the years, stuff that wasn't even in Jesus's playbook.

It might take a while, maybe decades or even longer, but mark my words, things are gonna change. It'll be like rewindin' a VCR, goin' back to the basics, back to Jesus's original message. Imagine folks gettin' rid of all that extra stuff, layer by layer, until all that's left is Jesus himself, plain and simple.

This change is gonna sweep through America and Europe faster than a wildfire, and folks are gonna start worshipin' like it's the good ol' days back when Jesus walked the earth. The church, well, they'll be leadin' the way, but things are gonna be different.

All these different churches, all these different ideas, it's gonna start to fade away. It'll be more like one big family again, everybody singin' from the same hymn book.

History's full of these big changes, like when the Romans went from persecutin' Christians to becomein' Christians themselves. Or how America went from slavery to havin' Black folks leadin' the way.

This time, it's gonna be about Christianity, goin' back to its roots, gettin' rid of all the fancy stuff, and comin' together as one.

And here's the secret sauce: folks are gonna start seein' Jesus's words differently, not just as plain words, but like stories and symbols.

Now, let's talk about where it all started.

Way back in the day, before Jesus came along, there was Judaism. It was all about one God, God's word, and the Hebrew scriptures.

The Jewish folks weren't all on the same page, though. They had their own groups, like the Sadducees, the Pharisees, the Essenes, and the Zealots.

Listen,  this book, "The Jungle", it shows us how folks, deep down, they're just plain greedy.  It's all about lookin' out for number one, ya know? They don't give a hoot about anyone else, especially if they're not makin' them rich.  

You see it right there in the bosses of these big factories. They just wanna make their companies bigger and bigger, no matter who gets hurt along the way.  They don't care about the smoke pourin' outta their chimneys, or the stinkin' mess from all the animals around the place.  It's all about the money, see?  Like that author, Sinclair, he says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". That's how bad it was, man. 

And the bosses, they don't care about their workers neither. They'll work 'em 'til they drop, then fire 'em without a second thought.  Back then, there weren't no rules protectin' folks, so the bosses could do whatever they wanted. It was a real dog-eat-dog world in that Packingtown. 

The workers were treated worse'n dogs, like slaves.  They were workin' themselves to death, but nobody helped 'em. Even the unions were just lookin' out for themselves. They were makin' money off the backs of the poor folks. 

It's a real sad story, man. Just shows how greed can corrupt people, and how the powerful can take advantage of the weak.

Some writers, they got tricks for makin' ya feel somethin' 'bout what they're writin', ya know? Some ways work better'n others. F. Scott Fitzgerald, he's one smart fella, he uses all kinds of tricks in his book, "The Great Gatsby". Sometimes he'll put words together that don't usually go together, like a "blue banana", just to make ya feel somethin' different about somethin'. Other times, he'll pick a color or somethin', give it a meaning, and then use that same color to make ya feel that same way 'bout somethin' important. He does that with colors all the time, like gold, green, white, gray, and even red and pink. 

In "The Great Gatsby", he builds up meanings for these colors, especially white and gray, and then uses 'em to make ya remember somethin' 'bout somethin' important. He uses white and gray to mean, well, kinda like boring sameness, like everything's the same. White's a bit fancier, and gray's more like old and worn out. He starts doin' this right at the beginning of the book. Daisy and Jordan are always wearin' white, like all the time! Nick wears white pants to Gatsby's party, Tom's wearin' a white shirt when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine's all pale and white.  The only time folks ain't wearin' white is when Nick's gettin' a feel for Gatsby's party, and then it's all bright colors, like nothin' like white. He uses these colors to describe all sorts of things, too, like Nick goin' to work down these white streets, or  names at Gatsby's party lookin' gray on Nick's list. Catherine's apartment, it's like a big white cake, all the same. He even uses white and gray for folks and places that ain't nothin' special, like Jordan and Daisy's childhood, the cars and the land in the valley of ashes, even a little kid and an old dog seller.

After he's used white and gray enough, he starts usin' 'em to show that somethin' ain't important or that it's just the same as everything else. He does this with Daisy first. After he don't use white or gray for a while, he starts describin' Daisy wearin' white in a white car. Now, we start seein' Daisy as less of a real person and more like somethin' Gatsby just wants, somethin' plain and boring. He keeps doin' this with Daisy, like describin' her fur collar as a gray haze. It's all about makin' ya feel somethin' about Daisy, somethin' kinda flat and empty.

San Diego's weather is perfect for growin' crops, y'all.  They got tomatoes, citrus, greens, squash, broccoli, all sorts of herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, even peppers. Folks in San Diego are real keen on eatin' organic, and there's a whole lotta demand for it. They got these farms that sell their food straight to folks, kinda like a club, and they're always got waitin' lists.  Organic eggs and milk are real popular too. Now, a lot of these organic farms, they're not just about the food. They let folks come out and see how they do things, even go for a hike or watch the birds.  It's a way for the farmers to make some extra dough, teach folks somethin', and it's good for the land. 


Now, organic farmin' ain't easy. It takes a whole lot more work, 'cause you can't just use all those chemicals to get rid of pests and weeds. And sometimes, you lose more crops than if you were usin' that stuff. Plus, a little farm like that can't compete with the big boys when it comes to makin' a profit.

But there's a whole lotta good things about it too. The land's healthier, you got more critters around, and that makes for a prettier place to live. So, if you're a farmer thinkin' about doin' things the organic way, there's some help out there. The government's got programs to help folks who wanna do right by the land and still make a livin'.

Take this piece of land I found, right next to Potrero. It's got chaparral, some grass that ain't from around here, and some oak trees. It's right next to the forest, and there's all sorts of critters livin' there, some of 'em rare as hen's teeth. This land's been around for a long time, first the Native Americans lived there, then some folks came along and raised cattle and cut wood.

Now, I found this organic farm not far away, and they're doin' things the right way. It gives you an idea of what could be done with that piece of land.

Well, let me tell ya, culture is a big ol' deal when you're tryin' to get somethin' done. It ain't just about what a culture *is*, it's about what it ain't too. You can't just say "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese folks are nice as pie" 'cause that ain't right.  Every culture's got its own way of doin' things, its own quirks and beliefs.  

When you're dealin' with folks from a different place, you gotta remember that you're lookin' at it through your own lens. It's kinda like lookin' at a picture through a funhouse mirror, ya know? You can see the shapes, but they ain't quite right.

So instead of tryin' to change 'em or judge 'em, just gotta accept 'em for who they are and play along. Especially when you're the one who's got less to bargain with. It's like showin' respect when you're in someone else's house, ya gotta treat their stuff with care.

Now, culture ain't just about countries, it's about companies too. Some companies are all about long hours and hard work, others are more laid back. You can tell a lot about a company by how folks dress, how they talk to each other, and who they hire. Some companies even encourage their employees to give back to the community, others are more focused on the bottom line.

But here's the kicker: even within a country, you'll find different cultures. Like back home in America, we got all sorts of different kinds of companies, from big corporations to small businesses, and each one's got its own way of doin' things.

And then there's values. Those are the real heart of a culture, the reasons behind the actions. If a culture values respect and harmony, they ain't gonna embarrass their boss to get ahead. But a culture that values a hard bargain might hold out longer.

So, before you go in to negotiate with someone, it's good to do a little homework on their culture. But don't forget to get to know the person you're talkin' to too. That'll help you make a real connection and get somethin' done.

So, these two fellas, Anselm and Aquinas, they both wanted to prove God exists, see? But they went about it different ways. Anselm, he's all about faith, like lookin' inside yourself and knowin'. He says, since we can even think about God, He's gotta be real, like, it's in our heads already.  He's sayin' you don't need no fancy proof, just trust what you know in your heart. 

Now, Aquinas, he's the kinda guy who wants facts, you know? He thinks you can prove God with your brain, like a puzzle. He lays out five reasons why God has to be there, like how things change, where stuff comes from, and how everything ain't just happenin' by itself. He's sayin' it all adds up to God bein' the missing piece. 

Both of 'em got good points, but neither one's got the whole picture, ya know? It's like, Anselm's sayin' trust your gut, and Aquinas is sayin' use your noggin. But neither one's gonna convince everyone.

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout this fella, Buddha, back in the ol' days, like way back when folks were just starting to figure things out.  He was some kinda prince, but he got tired of all that fancy livin'.  So, he said "screw this" and went off to find the truth. Turns out, he found it, became all wise and stuff, and started preachin'.  People listened, liked what he had to say, and bam!  Buddhism was born. Now, this one branch of Buddhism, called Theravada, is like the original recipe, been around for over 2,500 years.  But times change, right?  Even Buddha wouldn't recognize it today.  Like, in Sri Lanka, they do this water-cuttin' thingy every year.  Monks and regular folks, all chip in, and it's kinda important, even though Buddha never mentioned nothin' about it.  See, Buddhism ain't just about the big ideas, it's about the little stuff too, and it's changed over the years.  Both the monks and the regular folks who follow Buddha, they had to tweak their beliefs a bit.  Sometimes it's good, sometimes it's bad, sometimes it's just life, ya know?  We'll get into all the details, but first, let's talk about the basics.

Buddhists, they believe in three things: the Buddha himself, his teachings (called "Dhamma"), and the community of followers (called "Sangha").  Think of it like a three-legged stool, all gotta be there.  The "Dhamma" is like the rulebook, all written down in these ancient texts called the Tripitaka.  There's the Sutta Pitaka, which is like the main preachin's, the Vinaya Pitaka, which is the monk's code of conduct, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka, which gets all philosophical.  It's got all the heady stuff like "Anatta" (no soul), "Dukkha" (life is suffering), and "Anicca" (everything changes).  Get these ideas, and you can escape the cycle of death and rebirth, called "Sansara".  No more sufferin', no more desire, no more anger, no more delusion, just peace.  Now, the Vinaya Pitaka, it lays out the rules for folks who follow Buddha.  Regular folks gotta follow five rules: no killin', no lyin', no stealin', no messin' around, and no gettin' drunk.  Monks, they gotta follow a whole bunch more.  But the most important thing, the whole foundation of Buddhism, is the Four Noble Truths.  First, life is suffering.  Second, why we suffer is because we cling to things.  Third, we can stop suffering.  And fourth, there's a way to stop suffering, and that's through the Eightfold Path.

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout these here U.S. and Mexico fellas. They got themselves in a right ol' tussle back in the day, lasted somethin' like 57 years, from '36 to '93.  You know, like two brothers fightin' over the last piece of pie.  They even went to war over it, back in '46 and '48, the U.S. took Texas and all that southwest land from Mexico.  

Now, ain't this somethin' like when your neighbors always stealin' your lawnmower or somethin'?  Countries sometimes squabble over land, resources, and beliefs, ya know?

These two, they clashed over religion, culture, tradition, and even money.  Ain't that somethin'?  Just like how folks get their noses outta joint over who got the best BBQ sauce!

You see, the U.S. and Mexico, they're like those two brothers always at it.  The U.S. had a real hankerin' for Mexico's land, kinda like that fella who always wants the biggest slice of cake.  

Religion played a part too, just like when folks argue over who's got the right way to worship.  Americans back then, they weren't too keen on Catholics, kinda like how folks might not get along if one's a hunter and the other's a tree hugger.

Anyway, they had all sorts of disagreements, 17 of 'em, if you believe them books.  Most of it was over land and folks crossin' the border.  It was like a big ol' border dispute, with outlaws and bandits makin' trouble.

But eventually, Mexico kinda had to rely on the U.S. for help, kinda like when your neighbor needs to borrow your tools.  And the U.S., they started lookin' at Mexico's money more than their land.  So, the fightin' died down, like when two kids finally get tired of bickerin'.

Fifteen years ago, somethin' happened to me outta nowhere. This sickness, one I never even knew existed, hit me like a ton of bricks. I was a nurse back then, ya know? I went into it 'cause I wanted that safety and security, somethin' I never had growin' up. Everyone was always sayin', "You'll always have a job, folks get sick all the time!" So, even though I dreamed of bein' a scientist or maybe a journalist, somethin' like that, I stuck with nursing.  

But there I was, 46 years old, single, nothin' saved up, and couldn't work no more.  This sickness, it took everything from me. Fifteen years on disability now, and I'm nothin' but broke.  Every day's a fight, a struggle just to keep my head above water. My security, my safety, my pride, gone. Ain't nothin' for sure anymore, but one thing I know for sure: I couldn't have made it this far without my family and a few good friends. Believe me,  when disaster strikes, you feel mighty weak.

Life throws curveballs, big and small. You can plan all you want, but some things are just too much to handle alone.

I agree, we gotta stop relyin' on the government for everything. That whole system's rotten to the core.  But instead of everyone buildin' their own little fortresses, how about we start trustin' each other again? Help each other out, ask for help when we need it. That's what this country was built on: compassion, respect, and lookin' out for one another.

Sure, they talk about rugged individualism, but the truth is,  our forefathers didn't make it through tough times by themselves. It was by lookin' out for each other.

So yeah, be prepared. I am. Got my disaster kit, first aid, water purifiers, even plastic to cover the windows if things get real ugly. Flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and enough canned goods to feed a small army. If you got the land, grow your own food, learn to can it. That's a good idea, just like a wood stove, as long as you ain't livin' in an apartment.

But here's the thing: get to know your neighbors.

Listen up, folks! You ever wonder why critters are the way they are? Like, what makes 'em evolve into these crazy shapes? Well, some brainiacs back in the day, way back in 1917, said figuring out how life changes in math terms is like trying to herd cats! And guess what? They weren't too far off.  

But, some folks are tryin' somethin' new. They're usin' math to figure out how critters like these fancy snails, called Prunum, grow their shells. It's like, they take pictures of these shells, break 'em down into numbers, and then use computer programs to see what kinda crazy shell shapes they could come up with. 

Think of it like this: a shell's like a spiral staircase, goin' round and round.  Each step is a whorl, and the whole thing's built around a central pole, like the support in the middle. Now, these steps can grow bigger or smaller, and there are lines between 'em called sutures.  

Now, imagine makin' a blueprint for this shell staircase. You gotta figure out how big each step is, how far apart they are, and how they all fit together. That's what these scientists are doin'! They're tryin' to figure out the rules of how these shells grow, and maybe even predict what kinda new shell shapes could pop up. It's like a puzzle, but with real live critters!

Well, lemme tell ya, little ol' Indonesia ain't doin' too hot when it comes to keepin' babies alive. They been havin' the same old problems for the last ten years, nothin' much changin'.  

Sure, they doin' alright with clean water and bathrooms, hittin' all those fancy goals they got. But when it comes to makin' sure moms and babies are healthy, they fallin' way behind.  They ain't gonna make their goals by 2015 if they keep up like this.  

Why? Well, lemme break it down for ya.  They tryin' to say they got more midwives helpin' out with babies, 72% of 'em now.  But, a lot of these midwives are just regular folks, not real doctors.  They can't handle nothin' fancy, gotta get a real doctor if somethin' goes wrong. And that's why so many moms bleed to death after havin' babies.  

They also sayin' less babies are gettin' sick with diarrhea.  Maybe, maybe not.  They don't even know how many babies are gettin' checked after they born, so hard to say for sure.  But it ain't lookin' good.  

Now, they doin' barely any C-sections, just 4%.  That's low, y'know?  In the cities, they doin' 7%, but out in the country, it's only 2%.  Seein' as how everybody goes to the city for fancy stuff, that's a problem.  Rich folks gettin' the good stuff, poor folks stuck with nothin'. 

They got a whole lotta problems to solve, but the big question is:  Should they just keep doin' the same old thing, or should they fix the whole system?  Program-specific stuff is easier, quicker, and more focused.  But it can drain resources from other parts of the health system. 

They need to decide what's gonna work best, and fast.  Babies ain't gettin' any younger!

Victorian books are all about the little details and the fancy people who lived back then.  But there are two books, *Oliver Twist* and *Wuthering Heights*, that are kinda different. They have mystery and weird stuff going on, which wasn't really common in those books. This mystery stuff helps us understand the characters better, like what makes them tick and what they're really feelin'.

Here's a bit from *Oliver Twist*:

"Suddenly, his head was full of all these confusing thoughts. He felt like he was walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were yelling at each other. He could almost hear them talking. Then he realized he was talking to them... But then BANG! Gunshots! He heard people yelling and saw flashes of light, and someone grabbed him and dragged him away. Through all this chaos, he kept feeling this weird pain that just wouldn't go away."

These books use mystery a lot, sometimes through dreams or things that feel like dreams. In *Oliver Twist*, these strange happenings show us what's going on inside Oliver's head, his hurts, and how he sees the world around him.  When he gets shot, it's like he's reliving it all over again in a dream, even though he's trying to find help. This part shows how out of control he is, how bad he's hurt, and those visions of Sikes and Crackit just make it worse.  He gets so overwhelmed that he doesn't even notice who's carrying him away. He's numb to everything except the pain, which is constant and scary now, not just a shock. It makes you wonder who's really in charge of his life, because it sure ain't him! This shooting shows that Oliver has zero control over anything. Even when he's in danger, he can't even try to fight back. It's like Fagin has broken him, making him give up hope. Otherwise, you'd think he'd at least try to save himself.


*Wuthering Heights* also has mystery and dreams, but they work a little differently. *

A couple years back, I was workin' in this after-school program, helpin' out the little rugrats with their schoolwork.  I was pretty good at English and readin', so that's what I mostly did. One day, this little fella named Adrian - think he was in third or fourth grade -  needed some extra help. Now, this kid was speakin' perfect English, but his readin' was all messed up.  Some letters, he'd read 'em fine, others, well, he sounded like a frog tryin' to sing opera!  It was mighty strange. I figured maybe he was just slow, but something didn't add up.   

Then one day, while I was lookin' after a few stragglers, Adrian's momma walked in. Couldn't say a lick of English, just Spanish.  I was just learnin' a few words myself, but we managed to piece together what was goin' on. Turns out, Adrian knew how to read, just not the English alphabet real well.   

I guess that's why he was havin' such a hard time.  It was like he knew the words, but didn't know how to put 'em together right.

That's when it hit me, see?  It ain't always as simple as it looks.  Even if a kid speaks English, readin' it can be a real struggle.  

That's why I'm sayin' we gotta do somethin' about the language barrier in schools, especially here in California.  Adrian's story shows us that it ain't always about the kid not knowin' the language, sometimes it's about knowin' the alphabet and how to put the letters together.


Now, I ain't sayin' it's easy.  We gotta figure out what works best for each kid.  Dual language programs,  immersion, private tutors, ESL classes - all got their place, but there ain't no one-size-fits-all solution.  

The best thing to do is combine 'em all.

Y'all ever think about what's bigger than us, you know? Like, somethin' we can't even wrap our heads around? Some folks go to church, others hit the temple, some try to figure it out on their own.  Lotta folks just go with what their parents taught 'em, but some, they say "Nah, there ain't nothin' out there but what we can see." They live their lives in their own little world.

Me, I've changed my mind about things a time or two, you know? What I thought was important one day, ain't so important the next. We all gotta figure out our own way, our own beliefs. We're all lookin' for somethin' to guide us, somethin' to make sense of it all.

My old man, he loved cardinals. We were sittin' on the porch one day, rain comin' down like crazy.  He was lookin' out at the storm, kinda like he was lost in thought. He wasn't lookin' so good, skinnier than usual, hair all thin. He didn't meet my eyes much that day. I felt kinda scared, you know? I wanted to tell him I loved him, but talkin' about it just seemed to make it all too real. So I just hugged him, sat next to him, and watched the rain.

He passed away a few months later, right before my 22nd birthday. They tried to help him with medicine and all that, but it didn't really work. He just suffered longer. God, what kind of God lets that happen, I thought. I didn't say no prayers, not that night.  If God was out there, he'd stopped listenin' to me a long time ago.

I didn't want to watch him die. It was too hard. I wanted to remember him like he was, not like he was in pain. I knew him better than anyone else, better than his family did. I knew he wouldn't want me there. I just curled up in bed for a few days and waited for the news.

Nobody even called me.

Alright, so this here "Gothic Novel" thing, it's like a real head-scratcher. You got folks sayin' it ain't got no depth, then you got others swearin' it's got this whole "terrible sublime" thing goin' on.  It's like a mix of old and new, kinda like my runnin' mate ideas, ya know?

This fella, Ian Watt, he wrote somethin' called "The Rise of the Gothic Novel," and he says it's all a big ol' oxymoron 'cause it's both old and new.  He's talkin' 'bout how the first Gothic Novel, this "Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole, it took bits and pieces from old-timey romances and mixed 'em with this newfangled story-tellin' thing called the novel. Walpole, he called it a "Gothic Story," and he used all sorts of theatrics and nature stuff to make it somethin' special. 

See, back in the day, folks were usin' the word "gothic" for all sorts of things, like different people, styles, and even times. It was kinda like sayin' somethin' was old-fashioned or, well, kinda dumb compared to the "modern" stuff. But then you got this whole new way of tellin' stories, the novel, where the reader gets right up close and personal with the characters' thoughts and feelings.  And that's what made Gothic somethin' special, somethin' that could be both old and new at the same time.

One of the big things in Gothic Novels is this idea of "Chivalry." You got these knights, brave and honorable, and the writers, well, they kinda miss that in folks these days.  Walpole, he was writin' during a time when things were pretty messed up politically, and he was scared about what the future held. Maybe he thought those "good old days" of chivalry had disappeared, and he wanted to bring 'em back.  In his book, you can see this in characters like Frederic. He's described as this prince who's been through a lot, suffered some tragedies, and is supposed to be dead. He's got all these chivalric traits, like a knight in shining armor. But, ya know, it's all kinda over-the-top, which kinda sets the stage for the whole Gothic thing, with all its drama and excitement.

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout this 'supply chain' thing. It's like how ya get your stuff from wantin' it to havin' it in your hands.  It starts with a fella orderin' somethin', then it goes through all these steps: gettin' the stuff to make it, makin' it, stowin' it,  deciding where to keep it, gettin' it to the store, and finally, deliverin' it to ya!  This Keith Oliver fella, a smart guy, kinda made up the name 'supply chain management' back in '82. He said it's all about plannin', doin', and controllin' all those steps to make sure folks get what they want, quick and easy.

Now, there are six big parts to this whole shebang: makin' it, gettin' the stuff, keepin' track of it, decidin' where to put it, movin' it around, and knowin' what's goin' on all the time.  Smart business folks use these six things to make sure their customers are happy.

Makin' it's the first step. You gotta figure out when, where, and how to make the stuff.  Gotta know what folks want, right?  Look at the market, see what folks are buyin'. That tells ya what to make and how much. Then you gotta pick the right place to make it, one that can make it good and plenty, and keep the customers happy.  

After that, it's all about plannin' when to do what and keepin' the makin' stuff in tip-top shape.  Makin' things right is real important, 'cause if you mess it up, it costs ya time and money in the long run.  I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target, and they had rules for everything, from how the workers dressed to how they got stuff off the trucks.  Keepin' things organized makes things run smooth.

The next big part is gettin' the stuff. That means figuring out where to get the stuff you need and who to trust to make it for ya.  Sometimes, you might have different parts of makin' somethin' in different places.  You gotta pick the best place for each part.  And sometimes, you gotta get help from other companies, 'cause they're good at somethin' ya ain't.  That's called "outsorin'," and it can make things faster and cheaper, but ya gotta make sure they do a good job.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'. This here Ellen Page gal, she's out on the street with a sign sayin' Hitler's still alive in Burma. Now, Burma, that's that Southeast Asian country where them folks been havin' a real rough go of it. They got this military junta runnin' the show, and they ain't exactly known for their kindness. Back in 2007, they had these big protests, them monks all wearin' their saffron robes, callin' it the "Saffron Revolution." The government tried to shut 'em down, started gettin' rough, even attacked the monasteries.  They threw journalists in jail and even killed one, just for bein' there, a fella named Kenji Nagai. 

Now, this ain't nothin' new, see.  Governments always tryin' to keep folks quiet, keepin' all the power to themselves.  Back in Roman times, them emperors thought they were gods, rule everything.  Even them Japanese emperors, they think they're gods too, sent down to lead folks with cell phones and, well, that hara-kiri business. And don't even get me started on our own President, Bush.  He and that Ted Haggard fella, head of Stupid People Worldwide, they're always talkin' on the phone.  

You see, it's happened before, all over the world.  Like back in '89, them folks in Tiananmen Square, tryin' to protest the Chinese government, and the government just went and cracked down on 'em, killed a whole bunch of 'em.  And then there was that Rwandan genocide, Hutu folks killin' Tutsis, just because.  And let's not forget Hitler and the Holocaust, rounded up all them Jews and...well, you know.

Listen up, folks! This Duke Ellington cat, he's a legend in the jazz world, ya know?  He stuck around for a long time, and he knew how to make his band sound real good. Now, he wasn't always playin' the piano loud and flashy, but when he wrote music, man, it was somethin' else! He made tunes so fancy and complicated, they let each guy in the band show off their own style.  Ellington was like the ringmaster, settin' up the whole show so these guys could go wild and improvise.  But he also knew how to make sure everything fit together, like a well-oiled machine, makin' each note sound just right.  He knew how to make each instrument sing, and how to get them all workin' together like a team.  That's why he wrote some of the best jazz music ever!

This guy Grove, he wrote a book about music, and he said Ellington was a real innovator.  He used his singers like instruments, not just for singin' words, but for makin' the music sound different and more interesting. One of his tunes, "Creole Love Call," shows how he did that. It ain't no normal song, it's like a conversation between a voice and the instruments. The singer starts smooth and sweet, then gets rougher later on. Then you got this trumpet player, he plays kinda quiet and sad, but it's still real soulful. Then comes the clarinet, screamin' high notes, like it's tryin' to reach the sky!  And the whole band jumps in, makin' it a real party.

Ellington used all kinds of tricks like that in his music, makin' it sound like nothin' you've ever heard before. He knew how to make everything fit together, from the singers to the brass to the rhythm section. He was a real genius!

She's always felt like somethin' was missin'. Like there was a hole in her life that just wouldn't be filled. It started back when she was about 14, just gettin' into all that teenage stuff.  And it was still there at 17, three years later. By then, she figured out she wanted someone, not some shiny new gadget or somethin'. But no boys ever really caught her eye. Some tried to, ya know, win her over, but nothin' worked. She wondered about it a lot, tryin' to figure out why she didn't feel nothin' for anyone. She thought about it for years, had all these theories, but nothin' ever really stuck. So she just kept livin', always wonderin' about what she was lookin' for.

Life at home was usually pretty chill. Her folks were good folks, always calm and collected. They never fought, and even when she was pushin' back, tryin' to be independent, they never really got upset. She was the wild one in a calm family, always full of energy and fun. People liked her, she was a real sweetheart. 

But today wasn't a calm day. She was walkin' around the house, tryin' to figure out what she wanted to do with herself, when she heard her mom scream from the kitchen. It was a sharp, scared sound. She rushed in, worryin' somethin' was wrong.  "Mom! Mom, what's happenin'?" Her mom was on the floor, holdin' her side, makin' little "ow" sounds.  Her daughter rushed to her side. "Ouch... sweetie... I... need you to take me to... the hospital." She was talkin' in short breaths, in pain. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where to pick you up." Her mom pointed, and her daughter, strong from all the workouts she'd been doin', scooped her up and carried her to the car. She laid her mom down in the back and drove as fast as she could.

The hospital smelled like medicine and sickness, and she was scared, but all she could think about was gettin' her mom help. She carried her in and yelled for a doctor. A bunch of worried faces gathered around, they pushed a bed over and laid her mom on it. They rushed her off, and her daughter was left sittin' there, waitin' and worryin'.

Later, they found out her mom had fallen off a step stool while reachin' for a vase.

So listen up, folks! This here study is about this thing called the "Mediterranean Diet," or "Med diet" for short.  It's like a fancy way of sayin' eat your veggies, drink some wine, and enjoy life!  They found that folks who follow this diet, especially the "aMed diet" which is like the Med diet on steroids, are less likely to get those nasty heart problems, like heart attacks and strokes.  

See, the aMed diet is all about eatin' good stuff like fruits, nuts, and fish, and cuttin' back on the fatty meats and bad fats.  Plus, you can have a little wine with dinner, which ain't bad!

Doctors have been sayin' for a while now that this Med diet is good for ya, but this study really focused on strokes and heart attacks.  They followed a bunch of nurses for like 20 years and kept track of what they ate and if they got sick.

They used these fancy questionnaires to see what everyone was eatin', and they found that the nurses who ate the most like Mediterranean folks were less likely to have a heart attack or stroke.  It's like magic!

So there ya have it, folks.  Eat your fruits and veggies, drink some wine, and you'll be lookin' good for years to come!

Listen up folks, 'cause this here's a story about how our country, the good ol' USA, went belly up back in 2007.  Jobs disappeared faster than a squirrel up a tree, houses were worth less than a used tire, and even the big, fancy companies went bust. This mess ain't over yet, so let's figure out what went wrong and how to fix it, you hear? Well, it all started with some politicians playin' fast and loose with money. They pushed banks and companies to hand out loans to folks who couldn't even pay the electric bill. And meanwhile, these big shots at Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, they were packin' up those risky loans like Christmas presents, sellin' 'em off to everyone and their uncle.

Now, when folks couldn't keep up with their payments, the whole house of cards came tumblin' down. Banks were left with nothin' but empty pockets, and they passed the blame around faster than a hot potato. This whole thing started back in '99, when President Clinton was tryin' to stay in the White House. He wanted to look good for reelection, so he loosened up the rules on loans.  Back then, a fella named Steven Holmes, he was writin' for the New York Times, said right then and there that this was a recipe for disaster. He said it'd be just like the savings and loan crisis back in the '80s.  Well, ol' Steve was a prophet, wasn't he? 

Things got even worse 'cause folks were borrowin' money they didn't have, buyin' houses they couldn't afford. It was a real wild west out there. And then, the bubble burst. The price of houses went down faster than a greased piglet at a county fair. The big investment banks, they were left holding the bag, drowning in mortgage debts. Some of 'em went belly up, some had to sell themselves for peanuts, and the government had to step in and save the rest.

Alright, so there's this thing called exposition, right?  It's when you gotta lay out the story's background, kinda like explainin' things to a slowpoke.  Sometimes it can be good, like when you're really hookin' 'em in, but most times, it's like watchin' paint dry.   You know, when your readers are yawnin' and wishin' they were doin' somethin' else, like countin' the cracks in the sidewalk. 

Now, I'm sure y'all know the sayin', "Show, don't tell," but even I, ol' Dr. Merlin, trip up sometimes and get stuck in a whole mess of tellin' instead of showin'.  It's like when you're talkin' to someone and you just keep babblin' on and on about everything that ever happened, instead of just lettin' them see it for themselves. 

Exposition is like that talkin' fella in a movie who just spills the beans about everything.  It's like, "Hey, listen up!  Here's the whole story, from start to finish!"  

And trust me, nobody wants to hear that.  You gotta make 'em feel it, make 'em see it, make 'em understand what's goin' on without you just tellin' 'em every little detail. 

Let's say you're writin' a story about a gal who falls head over heels for this fella, they get hitched, and then BAM!  He gets whacked right in front of her.  You wouldn't want to spend two whole pages just tellin' us all that, would ya?  

No sir, you'd wanna show us how much they loved each other, how special he was to her, and how much she's gonna miss him.  You'd want us to feel the pain, to understand why she's so heartbroken.  

See, that's what exposition's all about:  makin' it real, makin' it feelin', makin' 'em care.  Don't just tell 'em the story, show 'em the story.

Man, lemme tell ya 'bout these newscasts I watched outta Columbus, Ohio. First one was NBC 4 this mornin' (August 13, 2011), live and all. Biggest story they had was this fella in Ashley, Ohio, stabbed his wife somethin' fierce. Didn't say her name, but the fella's name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mugshot, looked like a real piece of work. They only gave him two minutes or so, which seemed right for a story still cookin'. All they said was he stabbed her a bunch of times and got hauled away. 

Next up was this young fella, Travis Buyers, 18 years old, shot up in Sharon Woods. Critically injured, poor kid. No one caught yet, SWAT team lookin' for the shooter. That story felt short, ya know? Makes me wonder if it was 'cause he was a black man, or livin' in a black neighborhood. 'Cause you know how it goes, when a white kid or grownup gets in trouble, the media goes bonkers. But when it's a minority, they barely give 'em a mention. 

They did talk about a bullet hole in a Med-Flight helicopter, though.  .22 caliber, they said, from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offerin' five grand for any tips leadin' to the shooter. 

Then they had a little chat 'bout the rain and thunder comin' Saturday. Said it'd be in the eighties all weekend.  Short and sweet, like they wanted ya to keep watchin'. 

And then this robbery at a UDF on Clime Road, Columbus. They went on and on about the robber bein' a black man, dark-skinned, six-foot tall, a hundred and fifty pounds. Seemed like they were really hammerin' home that he was black, ya know? 

Last story was about this Rene Rodriguez, some kinda drug kingpin from Texas.  Convicted of sendin' weed to Ohio.  Funny thing, they said he got sentenced to "300" months, instead of just twenty-five years.  Maybe they thought that sounded meaner?  Oh, and they mentioned he was Hispanic, which didn't seem too important to the story, if ya ask me.

Brothers, man, they got this bond, like, nothin' can break it. You know, like when you're watchin' your own reflection, except it's your brother. It's love, pride, jealousy, even anger, all mixed up in there.  You see yourself in him, the good and the bad. And when things get tough, that's when you really see what that bond is made of, right or wrong.  But it ain't always pretty. That bond, it comes with baggage, ya know?

This story, "The Scarlet Ibis", it's all about that brotherly love, the good and the bad. These two guys, they're out there in this beautiful place, tryin' to do somethin' that ain't gonna work out. There's this pride, see, and it's like a fire, burnin' hot.  It starts with the older brother, he wants somethin' out of his little brother, someone to keep up with him, someone to share all the adventures. But the little brother, Doodle, he's different. He's got this heart thing, ain't gonna last long, and he can't do all the stuff the older brother wants to do.  Makes the older brother mad, makes him feel like he's been robbed. He even thinks about, well, let's just say he ain't happy with Doodle.  But then Doodle smiles at him, and it's like somethin' melts inside him.  

The story goes on, and you see that pride growin', and then, bam!  It all comes crashin' down.  They go on this last trip, and things go bad.  One brother makes it out, the other...well, you gotta read the story to see what happens. But it's all about that bond, about how love and pride can both hurt like hell.

Dang, that brain of ours is somethin' else!  It's like a complicated gizmo, always thinkin' and creatin'.   Back in the day, folks thought it was like a wax tablet, then a piece of papyrus, then a book, and now they're sayin' it's like a computer.   But listen, don't go gettin' too hung up on that, 'cause these fancy comparisons only go so far. 

See, all this thinkin' starts with our senses.  They take all these things we feel and hear and see and turn 'em into electrical signals.   The brain then takes those signals and messes with 'em, kinda like a recipe, makin' sense of 'em from the bottom up and the top down.

Let's say you see a black box on a white background.  The bottom-up stuff, that's like lookin' at the box's edges and color and sayin', "Hey, that's a box!".   But the top-down stuff, that's like your brain already knowin' what a box is and sayin', "Yep, that's a box, gotta be!"

Now, once the brain's got all that info, it's gotta decide what's important.  It's like a filter, lettin' in the good stuff and blockin' out the rest.  You see a whole bunch of grass, but your brain ain't gonna bother with every single blade.  But if someone calls your name in a crowed room, bam!  Your brain's all ears.

To keep all this goin', the brain's gotta store the info, too.   There's all kinds of memory, like short-term and long-term.   

Imagine you read a word.  Your brain stores it in a bunch of different ways: how it looks, how it sounds, and what it means.  Then it holds onto it for a bit, like somethin' you're workin' on right now.  And if it's important enough, it gets tucked away in long-term memory, like a file cabinet in your brain.

Now, how all that stuff gets organized is a mystery.   Some folks say it's like a web, where ideas are connected like threads.   But nobody's quite figured it out yet.

Alright, so this Huxley fella, he's got some beef with all this fancy technology and the way our money system keeps pushin' it.  In his book "Brave New World," he paints a picture of a messed up future where folks care more about bein' part of the crowd than bein' themselves.  They're all about instant gratification, like a bunch of kids hooked on candy.  And the big boss man, the World Controller, he's like the puppeteer, makin' sure everyone's thinkin' the same way.

Now, some smart folks who study stuff like money and power, they call themselves Marxists, and they see right through Huxley's story. He's talkin' about how things like sameness and makin' everything into a product, that's the problem.  It's like he's sayin' that our system is rigged, and the folks at the top are keepin' the rest of us in the dark about how it really works.

Think about it like this:  the common folks in Huxley's book, they're just slaves to their wants and needs. They're pumped up on instant pleasures, buyin' and spendin' like there's no tomorrow. The World Controller, he's the one pullin' the strings, makin' sure they stay happy and dumb.  It's like a big ol' illusion, man.

And the worst part is, nobody even notices! They're too busy chasin' their own tails to see the bigger picture. They're like sheep, followin' the leader without question.  Love, real feelin's, they're all gone, replaced by this phony, plastic happiness.  It's a real bummer, ya know?

So Huxley's story, it's a warning. He's sayin' that if we don't wake up and see what's really goin' on, we're gonna end up just like those folks in "Brave New World" - trapped in a world of fake happiness and empty promises.

I been goin' to this here University Park for a couple years now, 'bout two and a half, maybe four and a half semesters. Now, gettin' around this campus is a real pain in the neck for most folks, includin' me. Back when I was a freshman, they stuck me in one of them East Halls dorms, way out east, past the stadium and that big ol' Bryce Jordan Center. Walkin' from that place to classes over by Willard, right in the middle of campus, could take you nearly 25 minutes, especially if the weather was bein' a real crank, which it seems to do a whole lot 'round here in State College. I was talkin' to a fella who graduated just a bit before me, and he told me that these East Halls used to be way out in the sticks, surrounded by nothin' but empty land. But now, they built all these new things - sports fields, fancy buildings like that new Creamery and the health place, and a bunch of apartments. It's gettin' harder and harder to get around with all this new buildin' goin' on.

So, what's the answer? How are we gonna fix this mess?  In my book, the answer is bicycles.  But it ain't just about havin' bikes, it's about havin' a campus that works for folks who ride 'em.


I was talkin' to my friend the other day, and he just got back into ridin' after takin' a break for a while. He said he couldn't believe he ever stopped. "Bikes are the only way to go," he said, "It ain't cool to ride one for a while there, but it's the best way to get around." Bikes are good for ya, both physically and for gettin' places. A bowl of oatmeal and a little peddlin' and you can go 30 miles or more. Now, I live off campus, just as far from the center of campus as some of them dorms. Best decision I ever made this year was buyin' a bike. I got class in that Thomas building every day, and it's a good 25-minute walk from my place. But on my bike, I can make it in 5 minutes if I'm peddlin' hard. 

The only problem is, that road, Pollock Road, it's the straightest way to Thomas, but it ain't always the easiest to ride.  Yeah, walkin' is good too, but I'm too busy for that. If I didn't have my bike, walkin' would be the only way to get to class.  Walkin' to Thomas every day would take another 30-40 minutes out of my day, that's over two and a half hours every week. And that's not countin' all the other walkin' I'd have to do to get to class, appointments, and all that other stuff.  Just ain't got the time for that.
